Miners trapped underground in China - BelfastTelegraph.co.uk

Rescuers are working to free 17 miners trapped following a gas explosion at a coal mine in western China, state media reported.

Xinhua News Agency said the blast happened on Saturday evening.
Three other people working inside the mine at the time have been rescued.
Xinhua said the pit is mined by Dahuangshan Yuxin Coal Mining Co Ltd, which is owned by the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, a paramilitary organisation.
China has the world's deadliest mines, although the safety record has been improving in recent years as regulators have strengthened enforcement of safety rules.
A duty officer at Xinjiang work safety bureau said he had no information about the incident.
Andy Grove, the former Intel chief executive whose youth under Nazi occupation and escape from the Iron Curtain inspired an "only the paranoid survive" management philosophy that saved the chip maker from financial ruin in the 1980s, has died.
Republican presidential front-runner Donald Trump has confronted doubts about the depth of his knowledge of world affairs, delivering a sober speech to a pro-Israel crowd and outlining for the first time his team of foreign policy advisers.
The US government has said it may not need Apple's help to unlock an encrypted iPhone used by one of the San Bernardino attackers.
Extremists have attacked the European Union military mission in Mali, police said.